<DOC><DOCNO> AP890510-0291 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 1912EST</FILEID><FIRST>u f AM-InsiderTrading     05-10 0232</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Insider Trading,0239</SECOND><HEAD>SEC Charges 2 Lawyers with Insider Trading</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A partner in a Buffalo, N.Y., law firm and hisbrother-in-law agreed to settle civil Securities and ExchangeCommission charges Wednesday that he traded on inside informationabout a client corporation.   Without admitting or denying guilt, Henry M. Porter, agreed toreturn more than $78,000 in alleged illegal trading profits and payan equal amount in civil penalties.   Porter's brother-in-law, William Wolski, 40, of Marietta, Ga.,also settled civil insider trading charges with the SEC and agreedto return more than $37,000 in alleged illegal profits plus anequal amount in penalties.   The settlement remains subject to a judge's approval.   According to court papers, Porter, 51, of Buffalo, has been apartner since 1975 in the law firm of Lippes, Kaminsky,Silverstein, Porter, Matthias andamp; Wexler, which was general counselto Amherst, N.Y.-headquartered Mark IV Industries Inc.   The SEC charged in its civil complaint that Porter, traded inthe common stock of LFE Corp. and tipped Wolski in 1985, afterallegedly stealing confidential information from his law firm thatthe Clinton, Mass.-based corporation was a possible takeover targetby Mark IV.   The complaint also charged that in 1986 Porter tipped Wolskiabout Mark IV's then-impending tender offer for Gulton IndustriesInc. and that Wolski, who was living in Stamford, Conn., at thetime, traded on Gulton securities.</TEXT></DOC>